Normalizing a vector involves scaling it to have a length (or magnitude) of 1 while keeping its direction the same. Here’s a step-by-step process to normalize a vector in different programming languages:

### Python
In Python, you can use the `numpy` library to normalize a vector. Here’s an example:

```python
import numpy as np

# Example vector
vector = np.array([3, 4])

# Normalize the vector
normalized_vector = vector / np.linalg.norm(vector)

print("Original Vector:", vector)
print("Normalized Vector:", normalized_vector)
```

### JavaScript
In JavaScript, you can use the `filter` method to normalize a vector:

```javascript
let vector = [3, 4];

// Normalize the vector
let normalizedVector = vector.filter(function(v) {
    return v.length / Math.sqrt(v.length);
});

console.log("Original Vector:", vector);
console.log("Normalized Vector:", normalizedVector);
```

### Java
In Java, you can use the `Math` library to normalize a vector:

```java
import java.util.Vector;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class VectorNormalize {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Vector<Integer> vector = new ArrayList<>();
        vector.add(3);
        vector.add(4);

        // Normalize the vector
        Vector<Double> normalizedVector = new ArrayList<>(vector);
        for (int i = 0; i < normalizedVector.size(); i++) {
            double value = normalizedVector.get(i);
            normalizedVector.set(i, (value + 0.5) / Math.sqrt(value * value));
        }

        System.out.println("Original Vector: " + vector);
        System.out.println("Normalized Vector: " + normalizedVector);
    }
}
```

### C++
In C++, you can use the `std::vector` library to normalize a vector:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <cmath>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> vector = {3, 4};

    // Normalize the vector
    std::vector<double> normalizedVector;
    for (int i = 0; i < vector.size(); i++) {
        double value = vector[i];
        normalizedVector.push_back(value / std::sqrt(value * value));
    }

    std::cout << "Original Vector: ";
    for (int i = 0; i < vector.size(); i++) {
        std::cout << vector[i] << " ";
    }
    std::cout << "Normalized Vector: ";
    for (int i = 0; i < normalizedVector.size(); i++) {
        std::cout << normalizedVector[i] << " ";
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### MATLAB
In MATLAB, you can use the `norm` function to normalize a vector:

```matlab
% Example vector
vector = [3, 4];

% Normalize the vector
normalized_vector = vector / norm(vector);

% Display the original and normalized vectors
disp('Original Vector:');
disp(vector);
disp('Normalized Vector:');
disp(normalized_vector);
```

These methods will help you normalize any vector while preserving its direction.

